amman@amman:~$ # 3. Create a sample file and display initial permissions
amman@amman:~$ touch ~/project_workspace/docs/project_info.txt
amman@amman:~$ ls -l ~/project_workspace/docs/project_info.txt
-rw-rw-r-- 1 amman amman 0 Jul  3 23:35 /home/amman/project_workspace/docs/project_info.txt
amman@amman:~$ 
amman@amman:~$ # Explanation: touch creates an empty file, ls -l shows the default file permissions.
amman@amman:~$ 
amman@amman:~$ # 4. Check current umask value
amman@amman:~$ umask
0002
amman@amman:~$ 
amman@amman:~$ # Explanation: umask shows the default permission mask (0022 typically means new files get 644, directories 755 permissions).
amman@amman:~$ 
amman@amman:~$ # 5. Modify file permissions
amman@amman:~$ chmod 644 ~/project_workspace/docs/project_info.txt
amman@amman:~$ chmod 700 ~/project_workspace/docs
amman@amman:~$ chmod 750 ~/project_workspace/src
amman@amman:~$ 
amman@amman:~$ # Explanation: chmod 644 gives owner read/write, group read-only, others read-only. 700 gives owner full access only.
amman@amman:~$ 
